# Testing (RSpec, FactoryBot, shoulda-matchers, Hotwire)

## Stack and commands

- Run the full suite: `bundle exec rspec`
- Run one file: `bundle exec rspec spec/path/to/file_spec.rb`
- Run one example: `bundle exec rspec spec/path/to/file_spec.rb:42`

## Layout and spec types

- Mirror `app/`: e.g. `spec/models`, `spec/requests`, `spec/system`, `spec/services`, `spec/helpers`.
- `infer_spec_type_from_file_location` is enabled in `rails_helper` — put specs in the correct directory so `type:` is inferred; add `type:` explicitly only when needed.

## RSpec style

- Use `describe` / `context` with clear names.
- Prefer `expect(...).to` (not `should`).
- Prefer `let` for lazy setup; use `let!` when the example depends on side effects or creation order.
- Test behavior and public APIs, not Rails internals.

```ruby
# Prefer
expect(user).to be_valid

# Avoid vague examples with no assertion on behavior
```

## FactoryBot

- `FactoryBot::Syntax::Methods` is included — use `create`, `build`, `build_stubbed`, `attributes_for` without a `FactoryBot.` prefix.
- Use **`create`** when the example needs persisted records; use **`build`** / **`build_stubbed`** when the DB is unnecessary.
- Use **traits** for variants (e.g. transaction types); avoid copy-pasting setup across files.

```ruby
create(:transaction, :expense)
create(:user, email: "user-#{SecureRandom.hex(4)}@example.com") # when uniqueness matters
```

- Prefer **sequences** or unique values for attributes with DB uniqueness constraints — avoid the same fixed email/name across examples when the schema enforces uniqueness.
- Minimize **callbacks in factories** that `update` associated records (`after(:build)` / `after(:create)`). They make tests order-dependent and hide setup. Prefer explicit setup in the example or a dedicated service when refactoring.

## shoulda-matchers

- Use [shoulda-matchers](https://github.com/thoughtbot/shoulda-matchers) in **model** specs (and other layers where a matcher exists) to keep validation and association tests short and consistent: e.g. `belong_to`, `have_many`…`dependent`, `validate_presence_of`, `validate_uniqueness_of`, `have_secure_password`, `delegate_method`.
- Prefer a **`subject` block** (often `build(:user)` with FactoryBot) when matchers need a well-formed in-memory model (notably `validate_uniqueness_of` and `have_secure_password`).
- Shoulda covers **repetitive Rails “wiring”**; keep separate **`expect` / `it` examples** for domain behavior that matchers do not model (e.g. custom `User#to_accounts` logic).

## Mocks and test doubles

- **Default to real behavior** — persisted records via FactoryBot, real associations, and full request/system paths when practical. That exercises the same flows users and controllers use and catches integration bugs.
- **Do not overuse mocks or stubs.** Heavy mocking can make tests pass while the app is broken; prefer testing what the application actually does.
- Reserve doubles for **clear boundaries**: external HTTP/APIs, time or randomness you need to fix, or isolating a single unit when a full-stack example would be impractical.
- `verify_partial_doubles` is enabled in `spec_helper` — stubs on real objects must match real methods.

## Hotwire / Turbo

- **System specs** (Capybara + Selenium per Gemfile): assert on visible outcomes — text, elements, path (`have_current_path`). Capybara waits for async updates; avoid arbitrary `sleep`.
- **Request specs**: assert HTTP status and body (including Turbo Stream responses) without a browser.
- **Stimulus**: prefer system specs for integration unless the project adds a JS unit test runner; do not introduce Jest/Vitest unless the team adds it to the stack.

## Support files

- Shared helpers, matchers, and config live under `spec/support/**/*.rb`.
- Do not name support files `*_spec.rb` (they would run as specs).
- New files in `spec/support` are auto-required from `rails_helper`.

## Shared examples (RSpec) — request specs

- Prefer **`it_behaves_like`** (with shared groups defined in `spec/support/`) for **repeated request-spec behaviour** so examples stay in one place and read consistently across controllers.
- In this app, see **`spec/support/shared_examples/requests_authentication_and_errors.rb`**, which defines:
  - **`a request that requires sign-in`** — unauthenticated `GET` (or any `unauthenticated_request` proc) → `redirect_to new_session_path`. The host must set `let(:unauthenticated_request) { proc { get some_path } }`.
  - **`a request to edit a missing record`** — signed-in `GET` to an edit path for a non-existent id → `redirect_to root_path` (matches `ApplicationController#record_not_found`). The host must set `let(:missing_record_edit_path)`; use `IMPOSSIBLE_RECORD_ID` for the id. **Run inside `context 'when signed in'`** so authentication runs before the controller’s `find`.
  - **`a successful GET for a new form`** — `GET` `new_path` → `200`. The host must set `let(:new_path) { new_…_path }`.
- **Other repeated patterns** (not yet extracted; consider a shared group if you add more controllers and copy-paste the same `it` again):
  - `POST` create → `redirect_to` the resource index; `DELETE` → same; `GET` index → `200` and a page title in the body.
- When introducing a new shared group, add a **short name**, put it next to the helpers above, and document the **`let` contract** in a one-line comment above the `shared_examples` block.

## What to avoid

- Leaving `:focus` / `fit` / `fdescribe` committed in shared branches — use locally or via `.rspec-local`.
- Duplicating factory data across many examples when a **trait** or **let** would centralize it.
